Drag and drop of view onto other views and view groups have been supported since Android API level 14 and it does n&#39;t depend on Layout type. Views have methods called `startDrag()` and `OnDragListener()` to handle this action. To use dragging a view you register an `OnTouchListener` or a `LongClickListener` on the view which can be dragged like so:

    button1.setOnTouchListener(new View.OnTouchListener() {
        @Override
        public boolean onTouch(View view, MotionEvent event) {
            DragShadowBuilder shadowBuilder = new DragShadowBuilder(
                    view);
            view.startDrag(null, shadowBuilder, view, 0);
            view.setVisibility(View.INVISIBLE);
            return true;
        }
    });
To specify the picture used for the drag operation you can use `DragShadowBuilder`.

The views which can be drop targets should implement `OnDragListener` like below:

    constraintLayout2.setOnDragListener(new View.OnDragListener() {
        @Override
        public boolean onDrag(View v, DragEvent event) {
            int action = event.getAction();
            switch (event.getAction()) {
                case DragEvent.ACTION_DRAG_STARTED:
                    Log.d(TAG, &quot;onDrag: ACTION_DRAG_STARTED &quot;);
                    break;
                case DragEvent.ACTION_DRAG_ENTERED:
                    Log.d(TAG, &quot;onDrag: ACTION_DRAG_ENTERED &quot;);
                    break;
                case DragEvent.ACTION_DRAG_EXITED:
                    Log.d(TAG, &quot;onDrag: ACTION_DRAG_EXITED &quot;);
                    break;
                case DragEvent.ACTION_DROP:
                    View view = (View) event.getLocalState();
                    ViewGroup owner = (ViewGroup) view.getParent();
                    owner.removeView(view);
                    ConstraintLayout container = (ConstraintLayout) v;
                    container.addView(view);
                    view.setVisibility(View.VISIBLE);
                    break;
                case DragEvent.ACTION_DRAG_ENDED:
                    Log.d(TAG, &quot;onDrag: ACTION_DRAG_ENDED &quot;);
                default:
                    break;
            }
            return true;
        }
    });
In `DragEvent.ACTION_DROP` case you could define what happens when the user drops the drag-able item. As you can see in this case drag a view from a `ViewGroup` which can be a `Layout` and drop it in a `ConstraintLayout` that it&#39;s a `ViewGroup` as well.

